:INFO
Reading Your Mash
Most problems in sake brewing announce themselves early through smell and \
appearance. A healthy mash smells sweet, yeasty, and slightly fruity through \
the active fermentation phase, then transitions to a cleaner, alcoholic aroma \
as it winds down. Off-smells like nail polish remover, vinegar, sulfur, or \
barnyard indicate specific problems, most of which are fixable if caught early.

:PATH
Mash Smells Like Vinegar
A vinegar smell means acetic acid bacteria have gotten into your batch.
|
:INFO
Mash Smells Like Vinegar
A vinegar smell means acetic acid bacteria have gotten into your batch. This usually \
happens when oxygen is introduced to a mash that is past peak fermentation and has lower \
alcohol to suppress it. Prevention is the best approach: keep your fermenting

:PATH
Mash Smells Like Nail Polish Remover
Ethyl acetate produces a sharp, solvent-like smell and results from a stressed
|
:INFO
Mash Smells Like Nail Polish Remover
Ethyl acetate produces a sharp, solvent-like smell and results from a stressed yeast \
population fermenting at too warm a temperature. If your fermentation space climbed \
above 18 C (64 F) for an extended period, this is the likely cause. Move to a cooler

