|
:INFO
Fermentation Stalled Early
If bubbling stops before day 14 and the mash still tastes sweet rather than alcoholic, \
fermentation has stalled. The most common causes are temperature too cold (below 5 C / \
41 F), yeast nutrient deficiency, or shock from a large rice addition that

:PATH
Mash Has Pink or Orange Spots
Pink, orange, or red discoloration in a sake mash almost always indicates
|
:INFO
Mash Has Pink or Orange Spots
Pink, orange, or red discoloration in a sake mash almost always indicates contamination \
with wild yeast or bacteria, sometimes the pigment-producing Serratia marcescens. This \
batch should be discarded. Do not taste it. Sanitize all equipment thoroughly

:NOTE
When in Doubt, Smell First
Your nose is the most reliable diagnostic tool for fermented beverages. Before \
tasting anything from a questionable batch, smell it carefully. A batch that \
smells genuinely off should not be tasted. Fermentation gone wrong can produce \
acetic acid, butyric acid, or other compounds that are unpleasant but not \
dangerous, but contamination with pathogenic organisms is also possible in an \
unsanitary process. Err on the side of caution and start fresh.

:CHECKLIST
Sanitation Checklist for Next Batch
[ ] Wash all equipment with unscented detergent and rinse thoroughly
[ ] Sanitize with Star San solution (1 oz per 5 gallons of water) or metabisulfite
[ ] Allow all surfaces to air dry completely before use
[ ] Use clean, chlorine-free water (filtered or left to off-gas overnight)
[ ] Keep wild yeast sources like bread, fruit peels away from your brew space
[ ] Confirm koji-kin spore packet is sealed and within its use-by date
